# I think one way I could clean it for easier data readability would be to get rid of spaces and replace them with _
df.columns = df.columns.str.strip().str.lower().str.replace(" ", "_")

#Another way, per the tips suggestion, is renaming the codes to what they mean -- had to search them up for this
df = df.rename(columns={
    "4046": "small_hass",
    "4225": "large_hass",
    "4770": "xlarge_hass"
})

# The main thing I need to clean is the who geography issue -- so I could find each unique value, then sort them into US, Region, State, or Metro based on where they fit into the data
import pandas as pd

# get all unique values
geo_vals = df["geography"].unique()

# Define known categories and what they could be named as
us_labels = {"total u.s.", "totalus", "total_us", "total u.s", "totalu.s."} # Added "totalu.s." and "total_u.s." for consistent matching after removing spaces
major_regions = {
    "west", "northeast", "southeast", "southcentral",
    "midsouth", "greatlakes", "plains", "westtex/newmexico"
}

# list of U.S. states for matching (lowercase) -- this I searched up because I didn't want to mannually put in each state one by one
from us import states
state_names = set([s.name.lower() for s in states.STATES])  # uses 'us' package

# Define classification logic
def classify_geo(name):
    n = str(name).strip().lower().replace(" ", "") # Remove spaces for consistent matching
    if n in us_labels:
        return "US"
    elif n in major_regions:
        return "Region"
    elif n in state_names:
        return "State"
    else:
        return "Metro"

df["geo_level"] = df["geography"].apply(classify_geo)

# The rest of this I used chaptgpt support to see how to check to make sure I did it correctly, because I went through the rest of the lab and was off on somethings
#before
print("Value counts for geo_level:")
print(df["geo_level"].value_counts())

print("\nUnique geography names classified as US:")
print(df[df["geo_level"] == "US"]["geography"].unique())

# Print unique geography names that, after processing, match major_regions
print("\nUnique geography names that match major_regions after processing:")
processed_geo_names = df["geography"].apply(lambda x: str(x).strip().lower().replace(" ", ""))
matching_region_names = df["geography"][processed_geo_names.isin(major_regions)].unique()

# Ensure the date column is a datetime

Code 
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import seaborn as sns

# Filter to only metro areas (re-calculated as this cell was executed independently)
df_metro = df[df["geo_level"] == "Metro"].copy()

# Compute average total volume per metro area and get the top 5 (re-calculated)
metro_avg = (
    df_metro.groupby("geography", as_index=False)["total_volume"]
    .mean()
    .nlargest(5, "total_volume")
)

# Keep only the rows belonging to the top 5 metro regions (re-calculated)
top5_names = metro_avg["geography"].tolist()
df_top5 = df_metro[df_metro["geography"].isin(top5_names)].copy()

# Sort by mean volume so plots appear in descending order - set geography as categorical (re-calculated)
df_top5["geography"] = pd.Categorical(df_top5["geography"], categories=top5_names, ordered=True)
mean_order = top5_names # mean_order should be the list of top 5 names in correct order

# 5) make side-by-side boxplots; overlay every observation + the mean
plt.figure(figsize=(11,6))

# boxplots (one per metro)
plt.boxplot(
    [df_top5.loc[df_top5["geography"] == g, "total_volume"] for g in mean_order],
    labels=mean_order,
    patch_artist=False
)

# every observation (slight jitter so points don't stack)
for i, g in enumerate(mean_order, start=1):
    y = df_top5.loc[df_top5["geography"] == g, "total_volume"].values
    x = np.random.normal(loc=i, scale=0.06, size=len(y))
    plt.scatter(x, y, s=10, alpha=0.18, zorder=2)

# overlay the mean as a diamond marker
means = [df_top5.loc[df_top5["geography"] == g, "total_volume"].mean() for g in mean_order]
plt.scatter(range(1, 6), means, marker="D", s=40, zorder=3, color="red", label="Mean")

plt.title("Weekly Total Avocado Volume  Top 5 Metro Areas (by average)")
plt.xlabel("Metro Area")
plt.ylabel("Total Volume (units)")
plt.legend()
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

As we can see, LA, NY< Sallas/FT.Worth, Houston, and Phoenix/Tucson sold the most total avacoados, in that order

# Filter the data to include only the specified California regions and types
tbl = tbl[tbl["geography"].isin(geo_order)].copy() #
tbl["geography"] = pd.Categorical(tbl["geography"], categories=geo_order, ordered=True)
tbl["type"] = tbl["type"].str.lower()
tbl = tbl[tbl["type"].isin(type_order)].copy() # Use .copy()
tbl["type"] = pd.Categorical(tbl["type"], categories=type_order, ordered=True)
tbl["hass_size"] = pd.Categorical(tbl["hass_size"], categories=size_order, ordered=True)

# DColors for each -- searched up on chat what codes would be close to the colors I wanted
color_for = {"Small":"#D97706", "Large":"#16A085", "Xlarge":"#7E6BBF"}

# Create a figure and a set of subplots (1 row, 2 columns), sharey=True ensures both subplots share the same y-axis
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12.5, 5), sharey=True)

# Loop through each avocado type (conventional and organic) to create a subplot
for ax, t in zip(axes, type_order):
    # Filter the data for the current type
    sub = tbl[tbl["type"] == t].copy() # Use .copy()

    # Pivot the data to a wide format suitable for stacking, index='geography' makes geography the rows, columns='hass_size' makes hass_size the columns, values='proportion' fills the table with proportion values
    # .reindex(geo_order) ensures the geographies are in the desired order
    p = sub.pivot(index="geography", columns="hass_size", values="proportion").reindex(geo_order)

    # Ensure all size columns exist in the pivoted data (fill with 0.0 if not present)
    for col in size_order:
        if col not in p.columns:
            p[col] = 0.0
    # Reindex columns to ensure they are in the desired size order for stacking
    p = p[size_order]

    # Create an array for the x-axis positions of the bars
    x = np.arange(len(p))
    # Initialize the 'bottom' of the stacked bars to zero
    bottom = np.zeros(len(p))

    # Loop through each size to create stacked bars
    for col in size_order:
        # Get the label and values for the current size
        lab = size_label[col]
        vals = p[col].to_numpy()
        # Add the bar for the current size on top of the previous sizes
        ax.bar(x, vals, bottom=bottom, label=lab, color=color_for[lab])
        # Update the 'bottom' for the next size
        bottom += vals

    # Add a title for the subplot (conventional or organic) with styling
    ax.set_title(t, bbox=dict(facecolor="#D0D0D0", edgecolor="none", pad=6), fontsize=12, weight="bold")

    # Set the x-axis ticks and labels
    ax.set_xticks(x)
    ax.set_xticklabels(p.index, rotation=25) # Rotate labels
    # Set the y-axis limits
    ax.set_ylim(0, 1.05)
    # Set the y-axis ticks
    ax.set_yticks([0, .25, .5, .75, 1.0])
    # Format the y-axis labels as percentages
    ax.yaxis.set_major_formatter(PercentFormatter(1.0))
    # Add a horizontal grid for better readability
    ax.grid(axis="y", linestyle="--", linewidth=0.6, alpha=0.6)
    # Hide the top and right spines (borders) of the plot
    for spine in ["top","right"]:
        ax.spines[spine].set_visible(False)
    # Set the y-axis label only for the left subplot
    if ax is axes[0]:
        ax.set_ylabel("Proportion")
    # Set the x-axis label for both subplots
    ax.set_xlabel("Region of California")

# Create custom legend handles
legend_handles = [
    Patch(facecolor=color_for["Xlarge"], label="Xlarge"),
    Patch(facecolor=color_for["Large"],  label="Large"),
    Patch(facecolor=color_for["Small"],  label="Small"),
]


fig.legend(
    legend_handles, ["Xlarge","Large","Small"], title="size",
    loc="center left", bbox_to_anchor=(0.905, 0.5), frameon=True,
    fancybox=True, edgecolor="#DDDDDD"
)

# Add a main title for the entire figure
fig.suptitle("Proportion of Average Hass Avocado Sales by Size", y=1.03, fontsize=14, weight="bold")
# Adjust the layout to prevent titles/labels from overlapping, leaving space for the legend
plt.tight_layout(rect=[0, 0, 0.88, 1])
# Display the plot
plt.show()

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# Group by date and geography and calculate the mean average_price and median house price
# We group because there might be multiple entries per date/geography in the avocado data
df_trend = df_joined.groupby(['date', 'geography']).agg(
    avg_avocado_price=('average_price', 'mean'),
    median_house_price=('Median Sale Price', 'mean') # Use mean here since Median Sale Price is already a median
).reset_index()

# Create a color palette for the different regions
palette = sns.color_palette("tab10", len(df_trend['geography'].unique()))
color_map = {region: color for region, color in zip(df_trend['geography'].unique(), palette)}

# Create subplots for each California region
g = sns.FacetGrid(df_trend, col="geography", col_wrap=2, height=4, aspect=1.2, palette=color_map)

# Plot average avocado price as a line
g = g.map(plt.plot, "date", "avg_avocado_price", marker='.', linestyle='-', label='Average Avocado Price', color='blue')

# Create a secondary y-axis for median house price
def plot_house_price(x, y, color, **kwargs):
    ax = plt.gca()
    ax2 = ax.twinx()
    ax2.plot(x, y, marker='.', linestyle='-', color='red', label='Median House Price')
    ax2.set_ylabel('Median House Price ($)')
    # Add legend to the second axis
    lines, labels = ax.get_legend_handles_labels()
    lines2, labels2 = ax2.get_legend_handles_labels()
    ax2.legend(lines + lines2, labels + labels2, loc='upper left')


# Plot median house price on the secondary y-axis
g = g.map(plot_house_price, "date", "median_house_price", color='red')

# Set titles and labels
g.fig.suptitle('Average Avocado Price vs. Median House Price Over Time by Region', y=1.02, fontsize=16)
g.set_titles("{col_name}")
g.set_xlabels("Date")
g.set_ylabels("Average Avocado Price ($)")


plt.tight_layout(rect=[0, 0, 1, 0.98]) # Adjust layout to prevent title overlap
plt.show()

When comparing both the average avacado price and total avacado volume (measured in 1e7 as seen at the top of the graph) against median house rice in the four major california cities, we clearly see there is no meaningful relationship between avacado conssumption and house affordability

Avacdo prices fluctuate depending on season and year, and although there has been slight growth, it is NOTHING compared to the huge increase in house prices. Additionally, not only is their price that much more over 2015-2021, but not that many more are being bought, as seen by the second set of graphs. Both show us that prices are not up that dramatically from 2015 to 2021, nor are the amount being purchased, but what is up signifcantly is the median house price.

To conclude this, Millennials arent priced out of home ownership because of avacdo toast. The media might see these spending habits, but by looking at avacod purchase hisotry form 2015 - 2021 and comparing it to median house price, we see there is clearly something completely different at play here, something that is out of the mellianials occasional trendy avacodos hands. There is much larger economic and plotical factors impacting this, beyond the myth that Millennials cant afford houses, because they spend all their money buying avocado toast
